[1] Panicle blight, rice - Louisiana, Texas
Date: Tue 20 July 2010
Source: Delta Farm Press [edited]
<http://deltafarmpress.com/rice/louisiana-facing-rice-disease-at-harvest-0720/>


Panicle blight is affecting Louisiana rice as farmers in the southern
end of the state are gearing up for harvest, according to Johnny
Saichuk, Louisiana State University (LSU). He said that conditions
have been ideal for the disease with hot nighttime temperatures when
the rice plants were flowering.

He said the problem is not isolated to Louisiana. "Rice in Texas is
getting nailed."

Saichuk said the best prevention for panicle blight is to plant early
so the plants are in the flowering stage before the hottest days of
summer. The disease effects differ among varieties. 'Jupiter' appears
to have resistance, while CL111 is susceptible.

Saichuk estimated Louisiana has 550 000 acres [222 580 ha] of rice
this year [2010], roughly 80 000 acres [32 375 ha] more than 2009. He
said the crop was planted late, and farmers were late to flood their
fields.

[Byline: Bruce Schultz, LSU AgCenter]

