******
[2] Phytophthora blight, pumpkin - Illinois
Date: Mon 19 Jul 2010
Source: Journal Star [edited]
<http://www.pjstar.com/business/x550418901/Pumpkins-threatened-by-blight>


A wet [2010] spring has experts worried about blight that could have
an effect on the Illinois pumpkin crop. Because 95 percent of the
nation's processing pumpkins are raised in central and southern
Illinois, the possibility of blight in this area is a big concern,
said Mohammad Babadoost, University of Illinois.

"Some of the fields have heavy blight due to the wet conditions
earlier in the growing season," he said. "Right now we're scouting
and monitoring to see how we can save the crop. The blight is a nasty
pathogen. I've seen it destroy entire fields," he said. "When the
pumpkin industry experiences loss, it affects our state's economy."

The same pathogen nearly destroyed the state's pumpkin industry in
1999, said Babadoost. "Management of this disease requires intensive
work. To prevent this disease, we recommend crop rotation, followed
by seed treatment and routine scouting, especially of low areas in
fields." Fungicides can also can be applied if there is no standing
water in the fields. The pathogen may be present in run-off [water
from infested fields].

[Byline: Steve Tarter]

[Additional news stories:
<http://prairiefarmer.com/story.aspx/phytophthora/blight/is/popping/up/in/pumpkin/fields/across/the/state/9/39865>
and
